text<-c("And the days are not full enough",
"And the nights are not full enough",
"And life slips by like a field mouse",
                "Not shaking the grass.")
text
## [1] "And the days are not full enough"    
## [2] "And the nights are not full enough"  
## [3] "And life slips by like a field mouse"
## [4] "Not shaking the grass."

This is basically a character vector. Well turn it into a tidy text dataset so its easy to analyse.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
df<-tibble(line=1:4, text)
df
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##    line text                                
##   <int> <chr>                               
## 1     1 And the days are not full enough    
## 2     2 And the nights are not full enough  
## 3     3 And life slips by like a field mouse
## 4     4 Not shaking the grass.

Now we need to transform this to one-token-per-document-per-row.

library(tidytext)

df %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

library(tidytext)
tidy_books <- austen_books() %>%
  group_by(book) %>%
  mutate(
    linenumber = row_number(),
    chapter = cumsum(str_detect(text, 
                                regex("^chapter [\\divxlc]", 
                                      ignore_case = TRUE)))) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)
colnames(tidy_books)
## [1] "book"       "linenumber" "chapter"    "word"
tidy_books %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  filter(n > 600)

N-Grams

a_bigrams <- austen_books() %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2)%>%
  count(bigram, sort = TRUE)

bigrams_sepr <- a_bigrams %>%
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")

austen_nrc <- tidy_books %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
  count(word, sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()
## Joining, by = "word"
austen_nrc
## # A tibble: 6,830 x 3
##    word    sentiment        n
##    <chr>   <chr>        <int>
##  1 good    anticipation  1380
##  2 good    joy           1380
##  3 good    positive      1380
##  4 good    surprise      1380
##  5 good    trust         1380
##  6 time    anticipation  1337
##  7 thought anticipation   839
##  8 dear    positive       822
##  9 sir     positive       806
## 10 sir     trust          806
## # ... with 6,820 more rows
austen_nrc %>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 5) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title="Sentiment Analysis: Persuasion", x = "Contribution to sentiment",
       y = "Words")+
  theme_bw()

custom_sw <- bind_rows(tibble(word = c("miss", "john", "ill"),  
                                      lexicon = c("custom")), 
                               stop_words)
austen_nrcaj<-austen_nrc %>%
  anti_join(custom_sw)
## Joining, by = "word"
austen_nrcaj%>%
  group_by(sentiment) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 5) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~sentiment, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title="Sentiment Analysis: Persuasion", x = "Contribution to sentiment",
       y = "Words")+
  theme_bw()
